<subSubSection pageId="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,837,1584]" pageId="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,873,900]" pageId="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A genus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moreau" authorityYear="1881" box="[461,556,873,899]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Moridae</taxonomicName>
with a ventral light organ and differs from all other genera by having genital papilla separated from anus by several small scales, a large pelvic fin with all rays elongated (
<figureCitation box="[1238,1329,909,935]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[322,1264,205,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[322,1264,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Ventral view of abdominal region comparing with the pelvic fins, light organ (left arrow), anus (middle arrow) and genital papilla (right arrow). A. Pterophycis gen. nov., NMMB-P22891. B. Holotype of Physiculus dalwigkii, type species of Physiculus, MNHN 1996-1380, 190 mm SL. C. Physiculus chigodarana, NMMB-P16401, 118 mm SL." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3562845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3562845/files/figure.png" pageId="1">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
), and the following combination of characters: snout broad and rounded, not shelf-like; palatines and vomer toothless; swimbladder with elongate projections that attached to openings at rear of the skull (
<figureCitation box="[1044,1113,981,1007]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1671,1696]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,181,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[227,1361,181,1645]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsolateral view of head showing the anterior extension of swimbladder (arrowed). A. Pterophycis gen. nov., NMMB-P22891. B. Physiculus dalwigkii, type species of Physiculus, MNHN A.4502, 197 mm SL." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3562847" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3562847/files/figure.png" pageId="1">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); pelvic fin with 7 rays; first dorsal fin short-based, with 8 rays; second dorsal and anal fins long-based, their margins not indented.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,837,1584]" pageId="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1054,1080]" pageId="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
From Latin 
<emphasis box="[478,523,1054,1079]" italics="true" pageId="1">pter</emphasis>
means fin and 
<emphasis box="[698,770,1053,1079]" italics="true" pageId="1">phycis</emphasis>
, a cod, in referring to the diagnostic large pelvic fin of the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,837,1584]" pageId="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,1125,1152]" pageId="1">Relationship.</emphasis>
The presence of the light organ and two dorsal fins suggest that 
<taxonomicName authority="Ho, 2019" authorityName="Ho" authorityYear="2019" box="[1080,1213,1125,1151]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Pterophycis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1080,1213,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="1">Pterophycis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1219,1324,1126,1152]" pageId="1">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1219,1324,1126,1152]" pageId="1" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1858" box="[269,390,1161,1187]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Physiculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[269,390,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1">Physiculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="1843" box="[408,498,1161,1187]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Gadella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[408,498,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1">Gadella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1887" box="[558,645,1161,1187]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Salilota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[558,645,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1">Salilota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belong to “ 
<emphasis box="[786,923,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1858" box="[786,913,1161,1187]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Physiculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Physiculus</taxonomicName>
”
</emphasis>
subgroup (
<emphasis box="[1057,1119,1162,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Paulin, C. D." box="[1129,1290,1161,1187]" pageId="1" pagination="243 - 250" refId="ref4196" refString="Paulin, C. D. (1989 a) Moridae: overview. In: Cohen, D. M. (Ed.), Papers on the systemtics of gadiform fishes. No. 32. Science Series, Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, Los Angeles, pp. 243 - 250." type="book chapter" year="1989">Paulin, 1989a</bibRefCitation>
), which also includes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1902" box="[253,415,1197,1223]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Tripterophycis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[253,415,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="1">Tripterophycis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that has a light organ and three dorsal fins. It apparently shares many characters with the most specious genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1858" box="[390,511,1233,1259]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Physiculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[390,511,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="1">Physiculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of vomerine teeth and similar fin elements and position. However, two diagnostic characters that distinguish these two genera are the large pelvic fins with all rays elongate and the position of genital papilla (
<figureCitation box="[453,553,1305,1331]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[322,1264,205,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[322,1264,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Ventral view of abdominal region comparing with the pelvic fins, light organ (left arrow), anus (middle arrow) and genital papilla (right arrow). A. Pterophycis gen. nov., NMMB-P22891. B. Holotype of Physiculus dalwigkii, type species of Physiculus, MNHN 1996-1380, 190 mm SL. C. Physiculus chigodarana, NMMB-P16401, 118 mm SL." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3562845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3562845/files/figure.png" pageId="1">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, vs. 1B, C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,837,1584]" pageId="1">
In addition to these two diagnostic characters mentioned above, it can be further distinguished from the monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1887" box="[292,379,1377,1403]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Salilota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[292,379,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1">Salilota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, restricted in southern America, by lacking tooth patch on vomer (vs. small tooth patch on vomer in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1887" box="[257,344,1413,1439]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Salilota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[257,344,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="1">Salilota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 8 first dorsal-fin rays (vs. 9–12); and from the worldwide distributed genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="1843" box="[1248,1338,1413,1439]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Gadella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1248,1338,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="1">Gadella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with 12 species currently, by having chin barbel (vs. absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="1843" box="[768,858,1449,1475]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Gadella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[768,858,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="1">Gadella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and origin of anal fin slightly behind a vertical of that of second dorsal fin (vs. origin of anal fin well behind that of second dorsal fin). Members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1902" box="[1267,1429,1485,1511]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Moridae" genus="Tripterophycis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1267,1429,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="1">Tripterophycis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with 2 species restricted in the Southern Hemisphere, have their light organs situated at around the anus and three well-separated dorsal fins which can be easily distinguished from those of other genera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
